{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014iq4DxMk5TVTwhj9Y4aBhn","type":"tool_result","content":"    85→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    86→- [ ] `event_queue` table created via migration\n    87→- [ ] Partial index on `(scheduled_at) WHERE status = 'pending'` exists\n    88→- [ ] Status index for observability queries exists\n    89→- [ ] Status values constrained to: `pending`, `processing`, `completed`, `failed`, `dead`\n    90→\n    91→### FR-2: Event Producer API\n    92→\n    93→A minimal function that inserts an event into the queue. Designed to be called **within an existing DB transaction** so the event is committed atomically with the triggering operation.\n    94→\n    95→```typescript\n    96→// Signature\n    97→async function emitEvent(\n    98→  tx: DatabaseTransaction,   // existing transaction handle\n    99→  eventType: string,\n   100→  payload: Record<string, unknown>,\n   101→  options?: {\n   102→    maxAttempts?: number;     // default: 3\n   103→    scheduledAt?: Date;       // default: now (for delayed events)\n   104→  }\n   105→): Promise<{ eventId: bigint }>;\n   106→```\n   107→\n   108→**Usage example (in settlement worker):**\n   109→```typescript\n   110→await db.transaction(async (tx) => {\n   111→  // 1. Existing: write settlement outcome\n   112→  await settleGame(tx, roundId, outcome);\n   113→\n   114→  // 2. Existing: insert referral earnings (fast, inline)\n   115→  await insertReferralEarning(tx, referrerWallet, ...);\n   116→\n   117→  // 3. New: emit event for async processing (reward delivery, notifications)\n   118→  await emitEvent(tx, 'referral.game_settled', {\n   119→    referrerWallet, refereeWallet, roundId, gameType, wagerLamports, earnedLamports\n   120→  });\n   121→});\n   122→// All three committed atomically — or none.\n   123→```\n   124→\n   125→**Key property:** If the settlement transaction rolls back, the event is never created. No orphan events. No missed events.\n   126→\n   127→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   128→- [ ] `emitEvent()` function inserts into `event_queue` within the provided transaction\n   129→- [ ] Event is committed atomically with the triggering operation\n   130→- [ ] Default `max_attempts` is 3, overridable per event\n   131→- [ ] `scheduled_at` defaults to `now()`, supports future scheduling for delayed events\n   132→- [ ] Returns the created event's ID\n   133→\n   134→### FR-3: Event Worker\n   135→\n   136→A single polling loop that runs inside the existing backend process. No separate service, no separate deploy.\n   137→\n   138→**Polling loop:**\n   139→1. Every 1-2 seconds, query for ready events:\n   140→   ```sql\n   141→   UPDATE event_queue\n   142→   SET status = 'processing', started_at = now()\n   143→   WHERE id IN (\n   144→     SELECT id FROM event_queue\n   145→     WHERE status = 'pending' AND scheduled_at <= now()\n   146→     ORDER BY scheduled_at\n   147→     LIMIT 10\n   148→     FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED\n   149→   )\n   150→   RETURNING *;\n   151→   ```\n   152→2. For each claimed event, look up the handler by `event_type` and call it\n   153→3. On handler success → `status = 'completed'`, `completed_at = now()`\n   154→4. On handler failure:\n   155→   - Increment `attempts`\n   156→   - If `attempts < max_attempts` → `status = 'pending'`, `scheduled_at = now() + backoff(attempts)`\n   157→   - If `attempts >= max_attempts` → `status = 'dead'`, `error = error_message`\n   158→5. Log all state transitions for observability\n   159→\n   160→**Backoff schedule (exponential):**\n   161→- Attempt 1 failure → retry after 5 seconds\n   162→- Attempt 2 failure → retry after 30 seconds\n   163→- Attempt 3 failure → dead (manual review)\n   164→\n   165→Backoff is configurable per event type if needed, but defaults are fine for v1.\n   166→\n   167→**`SKIP LOCKED` is critical:** If the worker is slow or a handler takes a while, the next poll skips events already being processed. This prevents double-processing and enables future multi-worker scaling without code changes.\n   168→\n   169→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   170→- [ ] Worker loop starts automatically with the backend process\n   171→- [ ] Polls every 1-2 seconds (configurable via env)\n   172→- [ ] Claims batch of up to 10 events using `FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED`\n   173→- [ ] Successfully processed events transition to `completed`\n   174→- [ ] Failed events retry with exponential backoff (5s, 30s, then dead)\n   175→- [ ] Dead events have error message recorded\n   176→- [ ] All state transitions are logged (event_id, type, old_status → new_status)\n   177→- [ ] Worker gracefully stops on process shutdown (finishes current batch, then exits)\n   178→\n   179→### FR-4: Handler Registry\n   180→\n   181→A simple map from event type strings to handler functions. New features register handlers at startup — no queue code changes needed.\n   182→\n   183→```typescript\n   184→type EventHandler = (payload: Record<string, unknown>) => Promise<void>;\n   185→\n   186→const handlers = new Map<string, EventHandler>();\n   187→\n   188→function registerHandler(eventType: string, handler: EventHandler): void;\n   189→function getHandler(eventType: string): EventHandler | undefined;\n   190→```\n   191→\n   192→**Rules:**\n   193→- One handler per event type (not a pub/sub fan-out — keep it simple for v1)\n   194→- If no handler is registered for an event type, the event is marked `dead` immediately with error \"no handler registered\"\n   195→- Handlers must be idempotent — re-processing a completed event should be a safe no-op\n   196→\n   197→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   198→- [ ] Handlers can be registered by event type string\n   199→- [ ] Worker looks up handler for each event's `event_type`\n   200→- [ ] Unhandled event types are marked `dead` with descriptive error\n   201→- [ ] Handler interface is a simple `async (payload) => void` function\n   202→- [ ] Handlers are registered at backend startup before worker begins polling\n   203→\n   204→### FR-5: Idempotency\n   205→\n   206→Events may be processed more than once (crash during processing, worker restart). Handlers MUST be idempotent.\n   207→\n   208→**Pattern:** Before performing the side-effect, check if it was already done. For example:\n   209→- Claim handler: check if `referral_claims` already has a row for this event's claim_id\n   210→- Reward handler: check if reward was already granted for this round_id + referee pair\n   211→- Notification handler: check if notification was already sent\n   212→\n   213→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   214→- [ ] Each handler checks for prior completion before executing the side-effect\n   215→- [ ] Re-processing a `completed` event is a safe no-op (no duplicate SOL transfers, no duplicate rewards)\n   216→- [ ] Idempotency checks use the event payload (round_id, wallet, etc.), not the event_queue.id\n   217→\n   218→### FR-6: Observability\n   219→\n   220→Operators need to know when events are failing and when the queue is backed up.\n   221→\n   222→**Minimum observability (v1):**\n   223→- Log every state transition at INFO level: `[EventQueue] event=12345 type=referral.game_settled pending→processing`\n   224→- Log handler errors at ERROR level with full error + payload\n   225→- Dead events logged at WARN level with a clear \"MANUAL REVIEW NEEDED\" prefix\n   226→- Basic health stats available via internal endpoint or startup log: queue depth (pending count), dead count, processing count\n   227→\n   228→**Future (v2):**\n   229→- Metrics export (Prometheus/Grafana)\n   230→- Dead event alerting (Slack/PagerDuty)\n   231→- Admin UI for retrying dead events\n   232→\n   233→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   234→- [ ] All state transitions logged at INFO level\n   235→- [ ] Handler errors logged at ERROR level with payload context\n   236→- [ ] Dead events logged at WARN level with \"MANUAL REVIEW\" prefix\n   237→- [ ] Queue depth (pending count) queryable for health checks\n   238→\n   239→---"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8ac06484-cda2-401d-ad93-d5c7e79f4479","uuid":"dcc54ca4-059f-431b-a1e1-84530f85d27e","timestamp":"2026-03-21T21:33:26.038Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/docs/specs/301-async-event-queue/spec.md","content":"**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] `event_queue` table created via migration\n- [ ] Partial index on `(scheduled_at) WHERE status = 'pending'` exists\n- [ ] Status index for observability queries exists\n- [ ] Status values constrained to: `pending`, `processing`, `completed`, `failed`, `dead`\n\n### FR-2: Event Producer API\n\nA minimal function that inserts an event into the queue. Designed to be called **within an existing DB transaction** so the event is committed atomically with the triggering operation.\n\n```typescript\n// Signature\nasync function emitEvent(\n  tx: DatabaseTransaction,   // existing transaction handle\n  eventType: string,\n  payload: Record<string, unknown>,\n  options?: {\n    maxAttempts?: number;     // default: 3\n    scheduledAt?: Date;       // default: now (for delayed events)\n  }\n): Promise<{ eventId: bigint }>;\n```\n\n**Usage example (in settlement worker):**\n```typescript\nawait db.transaction(async (tx) => {\n  // 1. Existing: write settlement outcome\n  await settleGame(tx, roundId, outcome);\n\n  // 2. Existing: insert referral earnings (fast, inline)\n  await insertReferralEarning(tx, referrerWallet, ...);\n\n  // 3. New: emit event for async processing (reward delivery, notifications)\n  await emitEvent(tx, 'referral.game_settled', {\n    referrerWallet, refereeWallet, roundId, gameType, wagerLamports, earnedLamports\n  });\n});\n// All three committed atomically — or none.\n```\n\n**Key property:** If the settlement transaction rolls back, the event is never created. No orphan events. No missed events.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] `emitEvent()` function inserts into `event_queue` within the provided transaction\n- [ ] Event is committed atomically with the triggering operation\n- [ ] Default `max_attempts` is 3, overridable per event\n- [ ] `scheduled_at` defaults to `now()`, supports future scheduling for delayed events\n- [ ] Returns the created event's ID\n\n### FR-3: Event Worker\n\nA single polling loop that runs inside the existing backend process. No separate service, no separate deploy.\n\n**Polling loop:**\n1. Every 1-2 seconds, query for ready events:\n   ```sql\n   UPDATE event_queue\n   SET status = 'processing', started_at = now()\n   WHERE id IN (\n     SELECT id FROM event_queue\n     WHERE status = 'pending' AND scheduled_at <= now()\n     ORDER BY scheduled_at\n     LIMIT 10\n     FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED\n   )\n   RETURNING *;\n   ```\n2. For each claimed event, look up the handler by `event_type` and call it\n3. On handler success → `status = 'completed'`, `completed_at = now()`\n4. On handler failure:\n   - Increment `attempts`\n   - If `attempts < max_attempts` → `status = 'pending'`, `scheduled_at = now() + backoff(attempts)`\n   - If `attempts >= max_attempts` → `status = 'dead'`, `error = error_message`\n5. Log all state transitions for observability\n\n**Backoff schedule (exponential):**\n- Attempt 1 failure → retry after 5 seconds\n- Attempt 2 failure → retry after 30 seconds\n- Attempt 3 failure → dead (manual review)\n\nBackoff is configurable per event type if needed, but defaults are fine for v1.\n\n**`SKIP LOCKED` is critical:** If the worker is slow or a handler takes a while, the next poll skips events already being processed. This prevents double-processing and enables future multi-worker scaling without code changes.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Worker loop starts automatically with the backend process\n- [ ] Polls every 1-2 seconds (configurable via env)\n- [ ] Claims batch of up to 10 events using `FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED`\n- [ ] Successfully processed events transition to `completed`\n- [ ] Failed events retry with exponential backoff (5s, 30s, then dead)\n- [ ] Dead events have error message recorded\n- [ ] All state transitions are logged (event_id, type, old_status → new_status)\n- [ ] Worker gracefully stops on process shutdown (finishes current batch, then exits)\n\n### FR-4: Handler Registry\n\nA simple map from event type strings to handler functions. New features register handlers at startup — no queue code changes needed.\n\n```typescript\ntype EventHandler = (payload: Record<string, unknown>) => Promise<void>;\n\nconst handlers = new Map<string, EventHandler>();\n\nfunction registerHandler(eventType: string, handler: EventHandler): void;\nfunction getHandler(eventType: string): EventHandler | undefined;\n```\n\n**Rules:**\n- One handler per event type (not a pub/sub fan-out — keep it simple for v1)\n- If no handler is registered for an event type, the event is marked `dead` immediately with error \"no handler registered\"\n- Handlers must be idempotent — re-processing a completed event should be a safe no-op\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Handlers can be registered by event type string\n- [ ] Worker looks up handler for each event's `event_type`\n- [ ] Unhandled event types are marked `dead` with descriptive error\n- [ ] Handler interface is a simple `async (payload) => void` function\n- [ ] Handlers are registered at backend startup before worker begins polling\n\n### FR-5: Idempotency\n\nEvents may be processed more than once (crash during processing, worker restart). Handlers MUST be idempotent.\n\n**Pattern:** Before performing the side-effect, check if it was already done. For example:\n- Claim handler: check if `referral_claims` already has a row for this event's claim_id\n- Reward handler: check if reward was already granted for this round_id + referee pair\n- Notification handler: check if notification was already sent\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] Each handler checks for prior completion before executing the side-effect\n- [ ] Re-processing a `completed` event is a safe no-op (no duplicate SOL transfers, no duplicate rewards)\n- [ ] Idempotency checks use the event payload (round_id, wallet, etc.), not the event_queue.id\n\n### FR-6: Observability\n\nOperators need to know when events are failing and when the queue is backed up.\n\n**Minimum observability (v1):**\n- Log every state transition at INFO level: `[EventQueue] event=12345 type=referral.game_settled pending→processing`\n- Log handler errors at ERROR level with full error + payload\n- Dead events logged at WARN level with a clear \"MANUAL REVIEW NEEDED\" prefix\n- Basic health stats available via internal endpoint or startup log: queue depth (pending count), dead count, processing count\n\n**Future (v2):**\n- Metrics export (Prometheus/Grafana)\n- Dead event alerting (Slack/PagerDuty)\n- Admin UI for retrying dead events\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- [ ] All state transitions logged at INFO level\n- [ ] Handler errors logged at ERROR level with payload context\n- [ ] Dead events logged at WARN level with \"MANUAL REVIEW\" prefix\n- [ ] Queue depth (pending count) queryable for health checks\n\n---","numLines":155,"startLine":85,"totalLines":387}}}
